Mid Staffs: MPs put pressure on Sir David Nicholson to quit
MPs are piling pressure on Sir David Nicholson, the NHS chief executive, saying that it is “absolutely staggering” that he has not resigned over his role in the Mid Staffs hospital scandal.
Sir David Nicholson Photo: PA	By Peter Dominiczak, Political Correspondent
12:10PM GMT 04 Mar 2013
Follow Comments
Ahead of an appearance by Sir David in front of the Health Select Committee tomorrow, MPs accused politicians of "closing ranks" around the NHS over the scandal at Stafford hospital.
David Cameron has insisted that he has “confidence” in Sir David, despite a growing clamour for him to resign.
Charlotte Leslie, Conservative MP for Bristol North West, has tabled a Commons early day motion calling for Sir David to “face consequences” for the scandal.
It has now been signed by 20 MPs, including 15 Tories.
Sir David is the chief executive of the NHS and was the head of the strategic health authority charged with overseeing the hospitals in Mid Staffordshire. Related Articles
Choosing a GP means gambling with your life
07 Mar 2013
Mid Staffs: NHS chief refuses to resign
05 Mar 2013
Sir David Nicholson admits failings over Mid Staffs but refuses to resign
05 Mar 2013
NHS whistle-blower rejects evidence
05 Mar 2013
Mid-Staffs: Is Cameron's support for Nicholson wavering?
06 Mar 2013
Sacking Sir David Nicholson would 'falsely satisfy' Mid Staffs families, says Clegg
07 Mar 2013
Up to 1,200 people may have needlessly died at Stafford Hospital as a result of poor care, a public inquiry recently concluded.
Despite the report, none of the managers who oversaw the hospital have been sanctioned or punished. Sir David has apologised over the scandal but has resisted pressure from back-bench MPs and relations of the victims for him to resign. The Prime Minister has also repeatedly supported him remaining in position and his official spokesman today said that Mr Cameron believes that “Sir David is doing a very good job in his role as head of the NHS”. The Daily Telegraph last week disclosed that several Cabinet ministers privately believe that Sir David should stand aside. One Cabinet minister said Sir David’s position was “completely unacceptable” and symbolised how the Civil Service did not penalise failure. Several ministers are understood to have raised “very serious concerns” about Sir David but the Prime Minister has been advised by the head of the Civil Service that the NHS would be destabilised by his removal.
Miss Leslie said that it is “becoming more and more clear” that Sir David was “complicit” in the “disaster” at Mid Staffs.
Mark Field, the MP for the Cities of London and Westminster, said it was “mind-boggling” that Sir David is still in charge of the NHS.
He said: “I am always reluctant to see scapegoating, but given the seriousness of what happened at Mid Staffs it is absolutely staggering that nobody has been held accountable.
“Given how central his role was at the hospital, the public at large will find it extremely serious to see that he is now the chief executive of the entire NHS.
“It is very worrying that politicians of all colours seen to be closing ranks around the NHS over this whole issue.”
Sir David was chief executive of the strategic health authority overseeing Mid Staffs in 2005.
