A&E head suspended after he lifts lid on 'nightmare' hospital
By Nick Britten
12:01AM BST 22 Oct 2005
The head of an accident and emergency department has been suspended after attacking the "shocking and inexcusable" conditions at his hospital. Paul Lewis wrote to his managers describing a "nightmare" weekend in his overcrowded department at Grantham Hospital, Lincs, where patients were left on trolleys in corridors because of a shortage of beds. Mr Lewis, a senior nurse who has worked in the NHS for more than 30 years, even left the hospital to treat patients because he did not want them to be admitted. Managers sent him home after accusing him of misconduct for leaving the premises while on duty. In his letter, Mr Lewis described conditions during a 19-hour shift on Saturday, Oct 8. He said: "If you closed your eyes and thought this was happening in a Third World country, you would be very saddened by the events.
Related Articles
